CI/lint gate: fails the build if any `#[allow(...)]` or `#![allow(...)]` attribute appears anywhere in the repo's tracked/untracked-but-not-ignored `.rs` files. There is no allow-list or suppression mechanism in MVP — every match is a hard failure; the appeal mechanism is explicitly deferred.

Takes an optional root dir as `$1` (default `.`), `cd`s into it, and requires it be a git work tree (exits 1 with a diagnostic otherwise). File enumeration is deliberately `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard -- '*.rs'`, not a filesystem walk — a walk would descend into `target/` before pruning it and can race cargo/rust-analyzer writing there, causing nondeterministic aborts; git ls-files is a pure function of repo state instead.

The grep step always appends `/dev/null` to the file list so grep receives >1 path arg and therefore always emits the `file:line:` prefix, even when exactly one `.rs` file is tracked — this is load-bearing because ctx-verify's parser (elsewhere in the repo) splits output on `path:line:` and would break silently if grep switched to its single-file no-prefix output format. Match pattern is `^[[:space:]]*#!?\[allow\(`, anchored to line start (only catches attributes that start a line, not ones after inline code on the same line).

Exit code is 0 if no `.rs` files or no matches; otherwise prints one `FAIL: <path>:<line>:<matched text>` line per violation to stderr and exits 1. Uses `set -euo pipefail` plus explicit `|| true` after the grep pipeline so "no matches" (grep's exit 1) doesn't trigger the script's own `errexit`.